      "title": "Newton’s Shell Theorem",
      "subject": "AP Physics C: Mechanics",
      "summary": "# Newton’s Shell Theorem — AP Physics C: Mechanics\n\nNewton’s shell theorem is included in the gravitation unit of AP Physics C: Mechanics. Sources: [College Board AP Physics C: Mechanics CED](https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/media/pdf/ap-physics-c-mechanics-course-and-exam-description.pdf) and [MIT OpenCourseWare](https://ocw.mit.edu/courses/8-02t-electricity-and-magnetism-spring-2005/resources/16ff64d64187374a61c28a1f9f16f348_chapte4gauss_law/).\n\n## 1. The theorem\n\nConsider a uniform, thin spherical shell with mass $M$ and radius $R$. A test object of mass $m$ is located a distance $r$ from the center.\n\n### Outside the shell: $r>R$\n\nThe shell produces the same gravitational force as a point mass $M$ located at its center:\n\n$$\n\\vec F_g=-\\frac{GMm}{r^2}\\hat{\\mathbf r}\n$$\n\nand\n\n$$\n\\vec g=-\\frac{GM}{r^2}\\hat{\\mathbf r}.\n$$\n\nThe negative sign means that the field and force point toward the center.\n\n### Inside the shell: $r<R$\n\nThe net gravitational force and field are zero:\n\n$$\n\\boxed{\\vec F_g=0}, \\qquad \\boxed{\\vec g=0}.\n$$\n\nThis is true at every point inside a uniform spherical shell—not only at the center.\n\nAlthough the nearer side of the shell exerts a stronger force per unit mass, the more distant side contains a larger corresponding area. When all the force vectors are added, they cancel exactly.\n\nTherefore,\n\n$$\n\\boxed{\ng(r)=\n\\begin{cases}\n0, & r<R,\\\\[4pt]\n\\dfrac{GM}{r^2}, & r>R.\n\\end{cases}}\n$$\n\nFor an ideal infinitely thin shell, the field changes discontinuously at the surface, so the two one-sided results are normally stated separately.\n\n## 2. Gravitational potential\n\nTaking gravitational potential to be zero at infinity,\n\n$$\nV(\\infty)=0.\n$$\n\nOutside the shell:\n\n$$\nV(r)=-\\frac{GM}{r},\\qquad r\\ge R.\n$$\n\nInside the shell:\n\n$$\n\\boxed{V(r)=-\\frac{GM}{R}},\\qquad r<R.\n$$\n\nThus, the gravitational field inside the shell is zero, but the gravitational potential is not zero. It is a constant negative value.\n\nFor a test mass $m$, $U=mV$, so\n\n$$\nU(r)=\n\\begin{cases}\n-\\dfrac{GMm}{R}, & r<R,\\\\[6pt]\n-\\dfrac{GMm}{r}, & r\\ge R.\n\\end{cases}\n$$\n\nRemember:\n\n$$\n\\vec g=-\\nabla V.\n$$\n\nA zero gravitational field means that the potential has zero spatial slope, not that the potential itself must be zero.\n\n## Extension to spherically symmetric objects\n\nA spherically symmetric object can be divided into many thin concentric shells. At a distance $r$ from the center:\n\n- Every shell with radius smaller than $r$ acts as though its mass were concentrated at the center.\n- Every shell with radius larger than $r$ produces zero net gravitational field at that point.\n\nTherefore,\n\n$$\n\\boxed{g(r)=\\frac{GM_{\\text{enc}}(r)}{r^2}},\n$$\n\nwhere $M_{\\text{enc}}(r)$ is the mass enclosed within radius $r$.\n\nThis result can only be applied directly when the mass distribution is spherically symmetric.\n\n## Uniform solid sphere\n\nConsider a uniform solid sphere with total mass $M$ and radius $R$. Its density is\n\n$$\n\\rho=\\frac{M}{\\frac43\\pi R^3}.\n$$\n\nFor a point inside the sphere, $r<R$, the enclosed mass is\n\n$$\nM_{\\text{enc}}\n=\\rho\\left(\\frac43\\pi r^3\\right)\n=M\\frac{r^3}{R^3}.\n$$\n\nTherefore,\n\n$$\ng(r)=\\frac{GM_{\\text{enc}}}{r^2}\n=\\boxed{\\frac{GM}{R^3}r}.\n$$\n\nThe complete result is\n\n$$\n\\boxed{\ng(r)=\n\\begin{cases}\n\\dfrac{GM}{R^3}r, & r<R,\\\\[6pt]\n\\dfrac{GM}{r^2}, & r\\ge R.\n\\end{cases}}\n$$\n\nInside a uniform solid sphere, $g$ increases linearly with $r$. Outside the sphere, it decreases according to $1/r^2$.\n\nThe gravitational field is:\n\n- zero at the center;\n- largest at the surface;\n- proportional to $r$ inside;\n- proportional to $1/r^2$ outside.\n\n## Key AP Physics points\n\n1. **Check for spherical symmetry first.** The shell theorem cannot be directly applied to a hemisphere, cube, uneven shell, or off-center mass distribution.\n2. **Compare $r$ with the object’s radius.** Determine whether the point is inside, outside, or within the material of a thick shell.\n3. **Distinguish a thin shell from a solid sphere.** A thin shell has $g=0$ everywhere inside. A uniform solid sphere has $g=(GM/R^3)r$ inside.\n4. **Use enclosed mass inside a solid sphere.** Inside the object, $M_{\\text{enc}}\\ne M$.\n5. **Outer shells cancel.** They still exert gravitational forces individually, but their vector sum is zero.\n6. **Zero field does not mean zero potential.** Inside a thin shell, $g=0$ while $V=-GM/R$.\n7. **Use superposition for multiple shells.** Calculate the contribution from each shell and add the fields or potentials.\n\n## Common mistakes\n\n| Mistake | Correct idea |\n| --- | --- |\n| Gravity is zero only at the center of a shell | It is zero everywhere inside a uniform shell |\n| The object is attracted toward the nearer side | Contributions from the entire shell cancel |\n| Every spherical object has zero gravity inside | This is only true inside a hollow uniform shell |\n| Using $GM/r^2$ with total $M$ inside a solid sphere | Use the enclosed mass $M_{\\text{enc}}$ |\n| Assuming $g=0$ means $V=0$ | The potential inside is constant but generally nonzero |\n| Measuring $r$ from the surface | $r$ is measured from the center |\n| Applying the theorem to any round-looking object | The mass distribution must be spherically symmetric |\n| Saying outer shells exert no force | They exert forces whose vector sum is zero |\n| Writing gravitational-force magnitude as negative | Magnitude is positive; the sign represents direction |\n\n## Examples\n\n### Example 1: A point inside a thin shell\n\nA uniform thin shell has mass $M=9.0\\times10^{10}\\ \\mathrm{kg}$ and radius $R=4.0\\ \\mathrm m$. A $2.0\\ \\mathrm{kg}$ object is located $2.0\\ \\mathrm m$ from the center.\n\nSince $r<R$, the object is inside the shell. Therefore,\n\n$$\n\\boxed{F_g=0}.\n$$\n\nThe object does not need to be at the center for the force to be zero.\n\nIf the object is moved to $r=10.0\\ \\mathrm m$, it is outside the shell:\n\n$$\nF_g=\\frac{GMm}{r^2}\n=\\frac{(6.67\\times10^{-11})(9.0\\times10^{10})(2.0)}{(10.0)^2}\n\\approx\\boxed{0.120\\ \\mathrm N}\n$$\n\ntoward the center.\n\n### Example 2: Inside a uniform solid sphere\n\nA uniform solid sphere has mass $M$ and radius $R$. Find the gravitational field at $r=R/2$.\n\nThe enclosed mass is\n\n$$\nM_{\\text{enc}}\n=M\\left(\\frac{R/2}{R}\\right)^3\n=\\frac{M}{8}.\n$$\n\nTherefore,\n\n$$\ng=\\frac{G(M/8)}{(R/2)^2}\n=\\frac{GM/8}{R^2/4}\n=\\boxed{\\frac{GM}{2R^2}}.\n$$\n\nBecause $g_{\\text{surface}}=GM/R^2$,\n\n$$\n\\boxed{g(R/2)=\\frac12g_{\\text{surface}}}.\n$$\n\nA common mistake is to predict four times the surface field because the distance is halved. That reasoning fails because the enclosed mass also decreases.\n\n### Example 3: A uniform thick spherical shell\n\nA thick shell has inner radius $a$, outer radius $b$, and uniform density $\\rho$. Find the gravitational field within the material, where $a<r<b$.\n\nThe enclosed material has volume and mass\n\n$$\nV_{\\text{enc}}=\\frac43\\pi(r^3-a^3),\n$$\n\n$$\nM_{\\text{enc}}=\\frac43\\pi\\rho(r^3-a^3).\n$$\n\nThus,\n\n$$\n\\boxed{\ng(r)=\\frac{4\\pi G\\rho}{3}\n\\left(r-\\frac{a^3}{r^2}\\right)}.\n$$\n\nThe complete piecewise result is\n\n$$\ng(r)=\n\\begin{cases}\n0, & r<a,\\\\[6pt]\n\\dfrac{4\\pi G\\rho}{3}\\left(r-\\dfrac{a^3}{r^2}\\right), & a<r<b,\\\\[10pt]\n\\dfrac{GM}{r^2}, & r>b.\n\\end{cases}\n$$\n\n### Example 4: Work inside a shell\n\nA mass $m$ moves between two locations inside a uniform thin shell of mass $M$ and radius $R$.\n\nBecause $\\vec g=0$ everywhere inside the shell, $\\vec F_g=0$. The potential energy is constant:\n\n$$\nU=-\\frac{GMm}{R}.\n$$\n\nTherefore, $\\Delta U=0$ and $W_g=-\\Delta U$, so\n\n$$\n\\boxed{W_g=0}.\n$$\n\n## One-sentence summary\n\n> A uniform spherical shell acts like a point mass outside it and produces zero net gravitational field inside it; inside any spherically symmetric solid object, use only the enclosed mass.\n\nThe most important working equation is\n\n$$\n\\boxed{g(r)=\\frac{GM_{\\text{enc}}(r)}{r^2}},\n$$\n\nprovided that the mass distribution is spherically symmetric.",
